owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:comment: Primary marker: The base of the Greenlandian Stage is defined on the basis of the marked change in deuterium excess values that occurred over an interval of ca. 3 yr. Correlation event is end of the Younger Dryas cold spell, which is reflected in a shift in deuterium excess values
The Greenlandian GSSP is located in the borehole NGRIP2 in the central Greenland ice sheet at a latitude of 75.10N and a longitude of 42.32W.

owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:comment: The GSSP is defined in a speleothem (KM-A) with a modelled age of 4250yr bk2 (before AD2000), where the stable isotope profile shows a shift to heavier isotopic values, reflecting an abrupt reduction in precipitation due to weakening of the monsoon across the Indian sub-continent and southeast Asia. (https://timescalefoundation.org/gssp/detail.php?periodid=183&top_parentid=0)
The base of the Meghalayan Stage (Upper/Late Holocene Subseries/Subepoch) of the Holocene Series/Epoch is defined in the Mawmluh Cave speleothem in NE India and dated at 4250yr bk2 (before AD2000).
owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:label: Base of Meghalayan

owl:NamedIndividual.terms:source: International Commission on Stratigraphy - Formal subdivision of the Holocene Series/Epoch
owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:comment: Mawmluh Cave speleothem, Meghalaya, India. The Meghalayan GSSP is located in the northeastern Indian State of Meghalaya. The entrance of Mawmluh Cave is at the southern edge of the Meghalayan Plateau at a latitude of 25.262 N and a longitude of 91.715 W. The nearest town is Sohra (Cherrapunji).
owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:label: GSSP Base of Meghalayan

owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:comment: GSSP defined at the base of a silty mudstone layer (within bed 9) 52.8m above the base of the Kaili Formation in the Wuliu-Zengjiayan section in Jianhe County, eastern Guizhou Province, China. This level coincides with the first appearance of the cosmopolitan oryctocephalid trilobite Oryctocephalus indicus. Secondary indicators near the GSSP include the ROECE negative delta 13C excursion, the simultaneous appearance of acanthomorphic acritarchs, and a transgressive phase of a major eustatic event. The Wuliu-Zengjiayan section is situated along a hill ridge which is about 0.5km northeast of Balang Village, Jianhe County, GuizhouProvince, China at a latitude of 26.74738333 N and a longitude of 108.4138333 E. The GSSP is located inside the Jianhe Natural Reserve of Paleontological Fossils and the Miaoling National Geopark.

owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:comment: The Thanetian Stage concept was first used by Renevier (1873) who included the Thanet Sands with Cyprina morris and the Woolwich and Reading Beds with Cyrena cuneiformis. Its meaning was subsequently narrowed by Dollfus (1880), who included only the Thanet Sands, the original type-strata on the Isle of Thanet in southeast England. Since 1880 the term Thanetian has consistently been used with the restricted meaning of Dollfus (Bignot et al. 1997). https://doi.org/10.18814/epiiugs/2011/v34i4/002
